package Amazon::Lambda::Runtime::Builder;

use strict;
use warnings;

use Carp;
use Carp::Always;
use CLI::Simple::Constants qw(:booleans :chars);
use CLI::Simple::Utils qw(slurp slurp_json);
use Data::Dumper;
use File::ShareDir qw(dist_dir);
use English qw(-no_match_vars);

use Role::Tiny::With;

with 'Amazon::Lambda::Runtime::Builder::Role::CheckDeps';
with 'Amazon::Lambda::Runtime::Builder::Role::Install';

__PACKAGE__->use_log4perl( level => 'info' );

our $VERSION = '@PACKAGE_VERSION@';

use parent qw(CLI::Simple);

caller or __PACKAGE__->main();

########################################################################
sub init {
########################################################################
  my ($self) = @_;

  my $dist_dir = dist_dir('Amazon-Lambda-Runtime-Builder');

  my $manifest = slurp_json( sprintf '%s/MANIFEST.json', $dist_dir );
  $manifest = $manifest->{files};

  $self->set_manifest($manifest);

  $self->set_dist_dir($dist_dir);

  if ( my $profile = $self->get_profile ) {
    $ENV{AWS_PROFILE} = $self->get_profile;
  }

  return;
}

########################################################################
sub main {
########################################################################

  my %commands = (
    check   => \&cmd_dep_check,
    install => \&cmd_install,
    default => \&cmd_install,
  );

  my @option_specs = qw(
    help|h
    install-dir|i=s
    log-level|l=s
    profile|p=s
    force|f
  );

  my $cli = Amazon::Lambda::Runtime::Builder->new(
    commands      => \%commands,
    option_specs  => \@option_specs,
    extra_options => [qw(dist_dir manifest)],
  );

  $cli->run();

  return $SUCCESS;
}

1;

__END__

=pod

=encoding utf8

=head1 NAME

Amazon::Lambda::Runtime::Builder - Project scaffolding and environment
checker for Perl Lambda container images

=head1 SYNOPSIS

  # Scaffold a new project in the current directory
  alr-builder install

  # Scaffold into a specific directory
  alr-builder install --install-dir /path/to/my-lambda

  # Verify tools and IAM permissions before your first build
  alr-builder check

=head1 DESCRIPTION

C<Amazon::Lambda::Runtime::Builder> is the companion deployment tool for
L<Amazon::Lambda::Runtime>. It handles everything outside of the Perl
runtime itself: scaffolding a new project directory, verifying your build
environment, and documenting the full build and deploy workflow.

It provides two commands via the C<alr-builder> CLI:

=over 4

=item * B<install> - copies the project scaffold (Dockerfile, Makefile,
handler template, cpanfile, and test fixtures) into a target directory.

=item * B<check> - verifies that required system tools are present on
your C<PATH> and, if the optional IAM modules are installed, confirms
that your AWS credentials have sufficient permissions to build and deploy.

=back

=head1 COMMANDS

=head2 install

  alr-builder install [--install-dir DIR]

Copies the project scaffold from the distribution's C<share/> directory
into the target directory (defaults to the current working directory).
Creates the directory if it does not exist.

The following files are installed:

=over 4

=item * C<Dockerfile> - multi-stage build using C<debian:trixie-slim>.
The builder stage installs Perl, build tools, and your C<cpanfile>
dependencies via Carton. The runtime stage is a minimal image containing
only the Perl interpreter, runtime libraries, and your handler.

=item * C<LambdaHandler.pm.in> - handler template with stub
implementations for SQS, SNS, S3, and EventBridge events, plus a
streaming response example for Function URL invocations. Rename or copy
this file and customize it for your Lambda.

=item * C<Makefile> (installed as C<Makefile.build>, renamed on install)
- provides targets for the complete build and deployment workflow. See
L</WORKFLOW> and L</MAKEFILE TARGETS>.

=item * C<cpanfile> - starting point for your Perl dependencies. Add
modules here.

=item * Test fixture makefiles - C<sqs-test.mk>, C<sns-test.mk>,
C<s3-test.mk>, C<eventbridge-test.mk>, C<streaming-test.mk> - provide
targets for creating and testing each event source trigger.

=item * C<payload.json>, C<payload-sns.json> - sample invocation payloads
for C<make invoke> and C<make test-sns>.

=item * C<ecr-create-repo.mk> - creates the ECR repository if it does
not already exist.

=item * C<policies> - IAM managed policy ARNs to attach to the Lambda
execution role. Add one ARN per line; lines beginning with C<#> are
comments.

=back

=head2 check

  alr-builder check

Verifies that your environment is ready to build and deploy. Checks two
things:

B<Required system tools> - C<docker> and C<make> must be on your
C<PATH>. C<curl> is checked as an optional tool. Missing required
tools are reported as errors.

B<IAM permissions> - if L<Amazon::API::IAM>, L<Amazon::API::STS>, and
L<Amazon::Credentials> are installed, calls C<SimulatePrincipalPolicy>
using your current credentials to confirm your IAM identity has the
permissions required to build and deploy. See L</REQUIRED IAM PERMISSIONS>
for the full list.

If the IAM modules are not installed, tool checks still run but permission
checking is skipped with a warning.

=head1 OPTIONS

=over 4

=item C<--install-dir|-i> DIR

Target directory for C<install>. Defaults to the current working directory.

=item C<--log-level|-l> LEVEL

Log verbosity. Accepts Log4perl level names: C<trace>, C<debug>, C<info>
(default), C<warn>, C<error>, C<fatal>.

=item C<--help|-h>

Display usage information.

=back

=head1 WORKFLOW

The typical workflow for a new Lambda function:

=over 4

=item 1.

B<Scaffold the project>:

  alr-builder install --install-dir my-lambda
  cd my-lambda

=item 2.

B<Verify your environment>:

  alr-builder check

=item 3.

B<Implement your handler> - edit C<LambdaHandler.pm.in> or create your
own handler module. Add dependencies to C<cpanfile>.

=item 4.

B<First-time deployment> - builds the image, pushes to ECR, creates the
IAM role and Lambda function:

  make lambda-function

=item 5.

B<Test>:

  make invoke

=item 6.

B<Deploy subsequent changes>:

  make update-function

=back

=head2 Phase 1 - Build the container image

Lambda runs your handler inside an OCI-compliant container image. The
image must contain a Perl interpreter, your CPAN dependencies,
C<Amazon::Lambda::Runtime>, the C<bootstrap> entrypoint, the C<plambda.pl>
driver, and your handler module.

The installed Dockerfile handles all of this. Build with:

  make image

The key Dockerfile directives that wire everything together:

 ARG LAMBDA_MODULE=LambdaHandler.pm
 COPY ${LAMBDA_MODULE} /usr/src/app/local/lib/perl5

 ENV PERL5LIB=/usr/src/app/local/lib/perl5
 ENV LAMBDA_MODULE=${LAMBDA_MODULE}

 ENTRYPOINT ["/usr/local/bin/bootstrap"]

C<ENV LAMBDA_MODULE> tells C<bootstrap> which handler to load.
Set C<LAMBDA_MODULE> at build time to use a different handler module:

  make image LAMBDA_MODULE=MyHandler.pm

=head2 Phase 2 - Deploy and create the Lambda function

Once the image is built it must be pushed to ECR and the Lambda function
created or updated.

For a first-time deployment, a single target runs the full dependency
chain automatically:

  make lambda-function

This runs: C<ecr-repo> => C<deploy> => C<lambda-role> => C<lambda-policies>
=> C<lambda-function>. Each step is idempotent - re-running is always safe.
Sentinel files track completed steps so C<make> skips what already exists.

To deploy a code change:

  make update-function

This rebuilds the image, pushes to ECR using the image digest (never
C<:latest>), and updates the Lambda function code.

=head2 Phase 3 - Configure event triggers

The installed Makefile already includes all five trigger makefiles, so
all trigger targets are available immediately. Use whichever targets
apply to your Lambda:

  make lambda-sqs-trigger QUEUE_NAME=my-queue
  make lambda-s3-trigger  BUCKET_NAME=my-bucket
  make lambda-eventbridge-trigger
  make lambda-function-url
  make test-streaming

See L</MAKEFILE TARGETS> for the full list of targets provided by each
trigger makefile and the variables that control their behavior.

=head2 The policies File

The C<policies> file controls which IAM managed policies are attached
to the Lambda execution role. Add one policy ARN per line:

 # required - CloudWatch logging
 arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/service-role/AWSLambdaBasicExecutionRole

 # uncomment for SQS trigger
 # arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/service-role/AWSLambdaSQSQueueExecutionRole

 # uncomment for S3 read access
 # arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/AmazonS3ReadOnlyAccess

Apply changes at any time:

  make update-policies

B<Note:> receiving an event from a service does not automatically grant
your handler permission to call that service's APIs. An S3 trigger allows
Lambda to invoke your function - it does not allow your function to read
or write S3 objects. For broad access, add or uncomment the appropriate
managed policy ARN in the C<policies> file and run C<make update-policies>.
For access to a specific resource - a particular bucket, queue, or topic -
create a custom IAM policy that scopes the permissions to that resource ARN
and attach it to the execution role (C<ROLE_NAME>) via the AWS console or
CLI, then add its ARN to the C<policies> file so C<make update-policies>
keeps it attached on subsequent deployments.

=head1 MAKEFILE VARIABLES

Set these in your environment or pass as C<make> arguments:

=over 4

=item C<AWS_PROFILE>

AWS profile. Default: C<default>

=item C<REGION>

AWS region. Default: C<us-east-1>

=item C<REPO_NAME>

ECR repository name. Default: C<perl-lambda>

=item C<FUNCTION_NAME>

Lambda function name. Default: C<lambda-handler>

=item C<ROLE_NAME>

IAM execution role name. Default: C<lambda-role>

=item C<PERL_LAMBDA>

Docker image name (local). Default: C<perl-lambda>

=item C<LAMBDA_MODULE>

Your handler module filename. Default: C<LambdaHandler.pm>

=item C<PAYLOAD>

Payload file for C<make invoke>. Default: C<payload.json>

=item C<AWS_ACCOUNT>

AWS account ID. Resolved automatically via C<alr-helper get-account>
if not set. Set it explicitly to avoid the STS call:

  export AWS_ACCOUNT=$(alr-helper get-account)

=item C<TIMEOUT>

Lambda function timeout in seconds. Default: C<30>

=item C<QUEUE_NAME>

SQS queue name. Default: C<lambda-runtime>

=item C<BATCH_SIZE>

SQS messages per invocation. Default: C<10>

=item C<BUCKET_NAME>

S3 bucket for C<make lambda-s3-trigger>. Default: C<my-bucket>

=item C<S3_EVENT>

S3 event type. Default: C<s3:ObjectCreated:*>

=item C<RULE_NAME>

EventBridge rule name. Default: C<lambda-handler-test>

=item C<SCHEDULE_EXPRESSION>

EventBridge schedule. Default: C<rate(1 minute)>

=item C<INVOKE_MODE>

Lambda Function URL invoke mode. Default: C<RESPONSE_STREAM>

=back

=head1 MAKEFILE TARGETS

=head2 Primary Targets

=over 4

=item C<lambda-function>

First-time deployment. Runs the full dependency chain: ECR repository,
IAM role, policies, image build, push, and function creation. Run once
per function.

=item C<update-function>

Deploy a code change. Rebuilds the image, pushes to ECR, and updates the
Lambda function code.

=item C<invoke>

Test the function with C<$(PAYLOAD)> and print the response.

=item C<update-policies>

Re-attach policies after editing the C<policies> file.

=item C<clean>

Remove local sentinel files. AWS resources are not affected.

=back

=head2 Event Trigger Targets

=over 4

=item C<lambda-sqs-trigger>

Creates an SQS queue (C<QUEUE_NAME>) and attaches it as an event source.
Requires C<AWSLambdaSQSQueueExecutionRole> in the C<policies> file.

=item C<lambda-s3-trigger>

Configures S3 bucket notifications to invoke the Lambda on C<S3_EVENT>
events.

=item C<lambda-eventbridge-trigger>

Registers the Lambda as the target of an EventBridge scheduled rule.

=item C<enable-eventbridge-rule> / C<disable-eventbridge-rule>

Enables or disables the EventBridge rule without deleting infrastructure.
Use C<disable-eventbridge-rule> after testing to stop scheduled invocations.

=item C<delete-eventbridge-rule>

Removes targets and deletes the rule. Targets must be removed before the
rule can be deleted.

=item C<lambda-function-url>

Creates a Lambda Function URL with C<auth-type NONE> and
C<InvokeMode=$(INVOKE_MODE)>.

=item C<test-streaming>

Invokes the Function URL with C<curl -sN> to test streaming responses.

=back

=head2 Internal Targets

Called automatically as dependencies - you should not need to invoke
these directly:

C<image> - builds the Docker image.
C<ecr-repo> - creates the ECR repository if it does not exist.
C<deploy> - logs in to ECR and pushes the image using the image digest.
C<lambda-role> - creates the IAM execution role if it does not exist.
C<lambda-policies> - attaches all policies in the C<policies> file.
C<policy-document> - generates the IAM assume-role trust policy JSON.

=head1 REQUIRED IAM PERMISSIONS

The C<check> command verifies these permissions via
C<SimulatePrincipalPolicy>. You will need them to run the full build and
deploy workflow.

=head3 ECR

 ecr:CreateRepository         ecr:DescribeRepositories
 ecr:GetAuthorizationToken    ecr:BatchCheckLayerAvailability
 ecr:PutImage                 ecr:InitiateLayerUpload
 ecr:UploadLayerPart          ecr:CompleteLayerUpload
 ecr:PutLifecyclePolicy       ecr:GetLifecyclePolicy

=head3 IAM

 iam:GetRole                  iam:CreateRole
 iam:AttachRolePolicy         iam:PassRole
 iam:ListAttachedRolePolicies

B<Note:> C<iam:PassRole> is frequently overlooked. Its absence produces
a confusing C<InvalidParameterValueException> stating the role cannot be
assumed by Lambda even though the role exists and appears correct.

=head3 Lambda

 lambda:GetFunction              lambda:CreateFunction
 lambda:UpdateFunctionCode       lambda:UpdateFunctionConfiguration
 lambda:GetFunctionConfiguration lambda:InvokeFunction
 lambda:CreateEventSourceMapping lambda:ListEventSourceMappings
 lambda:GetPolicy                lambda:AddPermission
 lambda:RemovePermission         lambda:CreateFunctionUrlConfig
 lambda:GetFunctionUrlConfig     lambda:DeleteFunctionUrlConfig

=head3 SQS / SNS / S3 / EventBridge / STS

 sqs:ListQueues                  sqs:CreateQueue
 sns:ListTopics                  sns:CreateTopic
 sns:Subscribe                   sns:GetTopicAttributes
 s3:CreateBucket                 s3:ListBuckets
 s3:PutBucketNotificationConfiguration
 events:DescribeRule             events:PutRule
 events:PutTargets               events:RemoveTargets
 events:DeleteRule               events:EnableRule
 events:DisableRule
 sts:GetCallerIdentity

=head3 Handler Runtime Permissions

C<AWSLambdaBasicExecutionRole> covers CloudWatch logging only. Any AWS
APIs your handler calls directly require additional policies in the
C<policies> file. For example, a handler that reads S3 objects needs
C<AmazonS3ReadOnlyAccess> even if its trigger is an S3 event notification
- the trigger and the API access are governed by separate policies.

=head1 OPTIONAL DEPENDENCIES

IAM permission checking in C<check> requires:

=over 4

=item * L<Amazon::API::IAM>

=item * L<Amazon::API::STS>

=item * L<Amazon::Credentials>

=back

These are not hard dependencies - the tool is fully functional without
them, but C<check> will only verify system tools.

=head1 SEE ALSO

L<Amazon::Lambda::Runtime> - the runtime library your handler inherits from

L<Amazon::Credentials> - credential provider used for IAM permission checking

L<Amazon::API::IAM>, L<Amazon::API::STS> - AWS API clients used by C<check>

